 Synchronous and asynchronous programming refers to how code executes within your program. These two concepts are fundamental when dealing with JavaScript applications. Let's explain them separately before providing examples:

1) Synchronous Programming: In synchronous programming, each statement or block of code is executed one at a time, in the order they are written. It means that the execution of the next line of code depends on the completion of the previous line of code. In other words, if an operation takes more time to complete (e.g., fetching data from a server), the entire program will halt until the operation is completed.

Example:
```javascript
let result = 0;
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    result += i; // each iteration takes some time to complete
}
console.log(result); // prints '45' after the loop completes
```

2) Asynchronous Programming: In asynchronous programming, tasks can start executing before previous tasks have completed. It means that if an operation takes more time to complete (e.g., fetching data from a server), the program will not halt and other code will continue to run. The result of this task is provided when it completes.

Example:
```javascript
let result = 0;
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    setTimeout(() => {
        result += i; // each iteration will execute after a small delay
    }, 0);
}
console.log(result); // prints '0' immediately, not the expected '45', because the code inside setTimeout() is executed asynchronously
```

In the above example, the `setTimeout()` function makes the code within it execute after a small delay (0ms in this case). The `console.log(result)` statement executes immediately, even though all the iterations haven't completed yet because they are executed asynchronously. As a result, we get '0' instead of '45'.

To make it work correctly, we need to use callbacks or Promises:

- Using Callbacks:
```javascript
let result = 0;
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    setTimeout(() => {
        result += i; // each iteration will execute after a small delay
        if (i === 9) { // wait for all iterations to complete
            console.log(result); // prints '45' when the last iteration completes
        }
    }, 0);
}
```
- Using Promises:
```javascript
let result = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    let sum = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        sum += i;
    }
    resolve(sum);
});
result.then(res => console.log(res)); // prints '45' when the promise resolves
```

